application.

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:41.830
And, for me, having an
application which scales well

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:44.910
on the huge variety of devices,
that is the Android

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:48.400
landscape, is a big, big
part of that quality.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.470
So I think this is a really
important topic.

00:02:50.470 --> 00:02:53.320
ADAM KOCH: And one quick thing
I wanted to mention was I

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:56.960
really believe if you kind of
think about these responsive

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:59.830
web design or responsive Android
development from the

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:02.740
beginning of your development
cycle when building Android

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:07.950
apps, it can help you get that
tablet app or create designs

00:03:07.950 --> 00:03:11.610
that just really make it easier
to suit all different

00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:12.590
screens out there.

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:16.410
So rather than just designing
from the ground up, if you

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.300
just think about all these
things from the beginning, it

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:19.376
really helps.

00:03:19.376 --> 00:03:22.040
ROMAN NURIK: And before we jump
in again, just to talk a

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:23.760
little bit about the format,
we're not really going to be

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:26.340
talking about development
best practices.

00:03:26.340 --> 00:03:28.290
We do have several training
sessions on

00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:30.330
developer.android.com
on how to actually

00:03:30.330 --> 00:03:32.170
implement these concepts.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:35.150
But what we will do is we will
look into existing apps that

00:03:35.150 --> 00:03:39.620
are out there and see how they
treat or how they implement

00:03:39.620 --> 00:03:43.270
these responsive designs, how
they kind of scale fluidly

00:03:43.270 --> 00:03:46.080
across the different
device types.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:48.030
So let's jump in.

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:51.130
First, we're going to take
a look at Calendar.

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:53.800
So this is the built-in calendar
application that

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:58.050
comes with many devices, like
the Galaxy Nexus, the Nexus 7,

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:00.080
the Motorola Zoom.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:03.870
And this is an example of the
screen that lets you create a

00:04:03.870 --> 00:04:05.550
new calendar entry.

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:07.350
So on the phone here,
you see that--

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.850
and I'm going to go zoom
in for a second--

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:13.540
on the phone, you see that you
have a kind of Done, Cancel

00:04:13.540 --> 00:04:15.740
bar at the top, which is
basically replacing the Action

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:20.339
bar, and the different entry
fields, like the Calendar,

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:24.330
Event Title, the Date, Time,
things like that.

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:25.780
Pretty typical stuff.

00:04:25.780 --> 00:04:28.380
And then on the Nexus 7, you'll
see that it's switched

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:32.240
over into kind of a multi-column
layout where on

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:35.330
the left column, you have the
labels of the different text

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:36.410
entry fields.

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:39.240
And on the right, you have
the fields themselves.

00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:44.310
And then on the 10-inch
tablet in landscape--

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:46.040
I'm going to zoom in here.

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:47.350
Sorry about that.

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:49.730
You'll notice that it's
basically the same screen as

00:04:49.730 --> 00:04:53.270
the screen in portrait, except
it has wider margins.

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:57.700
So basically, they've decided
that, let's make sure that the

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:01.800
content, the text fields never
go past a pretty common

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:05.660
number, around 45 to
75 characters.

00:05:05.660 --> 00:05:08.720
Let's make sure that you can
never see more than that all

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:11.790
at once so that the line lengths
aren't too long.

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:15.630
So to fit that constraint,
let's introduce

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:18.350
margins along the sides.

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:24.560
So that's, in a gist, in a
nutshell, what the Calendar

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:27.660
app's Create Event screen
looks like.

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:29.640
Guys, any thoughts on other
things that they've done

00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:33.538
really well here to make sure
that this is responsive?

00:05:33.538 --> 00:05:34.780
NICK BUTCHER: I'd probably
just like

00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:35.910
to call out as well--

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:39.000
we talk a lot on this show about
Holo, about the visual

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.830
language of Android, the Holo
visual theme, and that it has

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:45.800
its own certain flat
look and feel.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.700
And I just wanted to call out
why that-- it's not an

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:50.650
accident that that kind
of design scheme

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:52.160
was chosen for Android.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.460
And I think this set of
screens here really

00:05:54.460 --> 00:05:58.810
demonstrates how Holo helps you
to create a user interface

00:05:58.810 --> 00:06:03.870
which scales nicely by using
typography and spacing

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:07.170
appropriately to give your
application structure, which

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:09.100
you can clearly see in
these three screens.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:12.480
That there isn't a lot of Chrome
subdividing boxes and

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:14.630
so on, text boxes and so on.

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:16.640
It really is the content
which defines the

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:18.240
structure of the page.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:20.520
And that really, really
helps it to scale.

00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:23.280
You haven't got lots and lots
and lots of different bitmap

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:26.510
assets or graphical assets or
gradients all over the place,

00:06:26.510 --> 00:06:30.500
which may look strange when
scaled up and wouldn't really

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:31.430
help you out in this field.

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:34.520
So I think this is one of my
major takeaways from looking

00:06:34.520 --> 00:06:37.760
at the Calendar application is
how Holo really, really, helps

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:41.290
out this app to scale across
these screen sizes.

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:44.020
ADAM KOCH: And one quick point
for me, if you look at the

00:06:44.020 --> 00:06:47.255
white space on the margins--

00:06:47.255 --> 00:06:49.610
let's see, if we zoom in here.

00:06:49.610 --> 00:06:52.260
So you can see on the phone,
you've got some white space on

00:06:52.260 --> 00:06:53.060
the left and right.

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:55.890
And then if you go up to the
Nexus 7, you'll see there's

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:57.760
slightly more white space.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:02.060
And then if you go across to the
landscape zoom, you'll see

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:05.380
they've actually got more white
space here that sort of

00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:09.760
makes everything fill out the
larger screen size there.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:12.640
ROMAN NURIK: It's important to
know that when you're creating

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:15.510
or defining these margins that
you still stick to a grid.

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:18.955
And as you can see in our design
guide under the Metrics

00:07:18.955 --> 00:07:22.800
and Grids section, we have this
concept of a 16-DIP grid

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:24.760
and a 48-DIP rhythm.

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:30.900
So using increments of 16 DIPs,
so 32 DIP or 48 or 64,

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:36.250
that can still introduce
structure into your layouts

00:07:36.250 --> 00:07:40.410
without constraining you to just
using very small margins.

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:44.750
So 32 DIPs, 48 DIPs, that's
great to use for larger

00:07:44.750 --> 00:07:47.002
devices, such as tablets.

00:07:47.002 --> 00:07:48.160
NICK BUTCHER: Yes.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:51.200
A naive implementation of this
kind of screen might have just

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:53.420
stretched the input fields all
the way across, which would

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:55.330
look pretty ungainly
on the 10-inch.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:58.050
So I think it's approaching your
screen design when you're

00:07:58.050 --> 00:07:58.870
designing an app.

00:07:58.870 --> 00:08:02.900
And if you see something which
is so barren, thinking about,

00:08:02.900 --> 00:08:06.250
hey, how is that going to look
on a much wider display, like

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:09.790
a 10-inch in landscape, for
example, and bearing in mind

00:08:09.790 --> 00:08:11.490
where you might want to
start introducing

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:13.756
these margin points.

00:08:13.756 --> 00:08:16.080
ROMAN NURIK: So let's move
on to the next app.

